 interactions with health navigators and emergency room staff, he shows us why millions of Latinx people avoid the healthcare system, even in times of need. With a compassionate eye, Vargas highlights the unique struggles Latinx people face as the largest racial group without health insurance in the United States. An intimate account of the lives of uninsured Latinos, this book imagines new, powerful ways to strengthen our social safety net to better serve our most vulnerable communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aHealth insurancezIllinoiszChicagovCase studies. 0aHispanic AmericansxHealth and hygienezIllinoiszChicagovCase studies. 0aHispanic AmericansxMedical carezIllinoiszChicagovCase studies. 0aMedical carezIllinoiszChicagovCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aAffordable Care Act.  aBureaucracy.  aCollege.  aCommunity Based Organizations.  aCriminal Records.  aCriminalization.  aExpungement.  aFamily Networks.  aFamily.  aFriends.  aGender.  aHealth Care Access.  aHealth Care Reform.  aHealth Insurance.  aHealth Services.  aInformal Economy.  aIntersectionality.  aJobs.  aLabor Market.  aLatinos.  aMedicaid.  aMedical Care.  aMedically Uninsured Persons.  aOrganizational embeddedness.  aPatriarchy.  aPolicy Feedback.  aPolicy.  aRace.  aReentry.  aSocial Movements.  aSocial Safety Net.  aSocial networks.  aUrban Poverty.  aWelfare.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075162840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479807260423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479807260/original  a978-3-11-075162-8  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN